<p>With a simple model:</p>  <pre><code>class Card(models.Model):     name = models.CharField(max_length=25)     rate = models.IntegerField(default=0)     good = models.BooleanField(default=False) </code></pre>  <p>it is possible to generate a form with:</p>  <pre><code>class CardForm(ModelForm):     class Meta:         model = Card         fields = '__all__' </code></pre>  <p>which then includes <strong>all</strong> the model fields through a simple template with major part as:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;table&gt;   {{ form.as_table }} &lt;/table&gt; </code></pre>  <p>But when showing through a <code>ListView</code> subclass as:</p>  <pre><code>class CardShow(ListView):     model = Card     template_name = 'myapp/show.html' </code></pre>  <p>it still requires a template where all the model fields are <strong>explicitly</strong> named as:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;ul&gt;   {% for card in object_list %}     &lt;li&gt;{{ card.name }}, {{ card.rate }}, {{ card.good }}&lt;/li&gt;   {% endfor %} &lt;/ul&gt;  </code></pre>  <p>Is there any way to auto-generate HTML code for view (show), just like the form has <code>form.as_table</code>, <code>form.as_p</code>, and <code>form.as_ul</code>?</p>